// TEST: exec_core_error
// EXPECT: output "boom;again: boom"
// EXPECT: targets rust, go
//
// THE PAYOFF FIXTURE for `core.error`: a user program that `use`s the embedded
// `core.error` stdlib module, constructs a `SimpleError` via the `error(...)`
// constructor, and reads its message back through the `message()` method —
// compiled + run on the targets where a struct field and a method may share a
// name today (rust + go).
//
// Q-GO-ERROR-MESSAGE LOCK. `core.error` declares `record SimpleError { message:
// String }` *and* `fn message(self) -> String` (the `Error` trait method). On
// Go those previously both emitted `Message` on the `SimpleError` struct — a
// field and a method with the same name, which `go build` rejects ("type
// SimpleError has both field and method named Message"), so `.message()` never
// compiled on Go. The Go backend now disambiguates the *method* to
// `MessageMethod()` (at the trait interface, the receiver, and every call site)
// while the field stays `Message`, so `go run .` compiles and runs. Rust allows
// a field and a method to share a name, so it is a no-op regression guard there.
//
// TARGETS — rust + go only. The SAME field/method name collision is a
// PRE-EXISTING bug on js, ts, and python (FOUND, surfaced for triage): on those
// targets the emitted instance field shadows the same-named method (TS: a
// `tsc` "Duplicate identifier" error; JS: `e.message` resolves to the string,
// so `e.message()` is "not a function"; Python: the dataclass field overwrites
// the method). The collision-disambiguation fix landed for Go here; the js/ts/
// python equivalents are a separate follow-up, so this fixture restricts to the
// two targets where `core.error.message()` works end to end.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

use core.error.{SimpleError, error}

fn read(e: SimpleError) -> String {
  e.message()
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let e = error("boom")
  let direct: String = e.message()
  let again: String = read(error("boom"))
  println("${direct};again: ${again}")
}
